    "prose": "The spiral stairs curved upward through damp shadow. Mira counted stones by memory—seventy-two to the gear room landing—but her attention snagged on what she was not hearing. The water wheel below should have been grinding against its bearings, a low bone-deep rumble she felt in her teeth during every inspection. \n\nThere was only silence.\n\nShe stopped on the thirty-eighth stair. Listened. The slosh of the river. Wind through the bell louvers above. Nothing from the channel below.\n\nMira resumed climbing, faster now. The worn stone dipped under her boots where generations of watchmen had placed the same foot. She did not touch the wall. The grease film on the stone was thick enough to stain wool.\n\nThe gear room door was iron-strapped oak. She pulled the key from her belt, fitted it into the lock. The mechanism turned with its usual reluctant scrape. She pushed the door open and the smell hit her—hot metal and burnt grease. A working gear train smelled of oil and river water. A stalled one smelled of friction cooking the lubricant into varnish.\n\nShe stepped inside.\n\nThe main gear hung motionless in its iron frame. Its teeth should have been meshing with the pinion shaft that drove the bell hammer. Instead, a jagged length of oak—a broken spoke from the water wheel's upper rim—lay wedged across three gear teeth and jammed against the housing.\n\nMira crossed to the gear and crouched. She did not touch the spoke. The splintered end was pale wood, still bleeding sap. Fresh. This break happened within the last hour, likely during the change of current when the river rose.\n\nShe straightened and checked the pinion. Fine. The cam shaft. Fine. The hammer linkage. Undamaged. If she cleared the jam, the mechanism would function.\n\nThe spoke was driven deep. The pressure of the wheel's own weight had forced it into the gap. Pulling it free by hand would be impossible. She needed leverage.\n\nMira turned and scanned the gear room walls. The pry bar hung on its hooks beside the spare spoke rack. She crossed to it, lifted the iron bar from its brackets. The weight was familiar in her hands.\n\nShe returned to the main gear and set the flat end of the pry bar against the jammed spoke.\n\nNow."
  },
