    "beat_index": 1,
    "beat_id": "ch-001-jammed-gear-beat-002-mira-tries-free-gear-pry",
    "beat_description": "Mira tries to free the gear with a pry bar but the spoke is wedged tight. She decides she must report this to the reeve immediately, despite the late hour.",
    "planned_characters": [
      "Mira Vale"
    ],
    "prose": "She heaved. The iron bar bent against the spoke, the metal groaning in protest. Nothing moved. Not a finger’s width. Not a hair.\n\nMira reset her stance, braced a boot against the gear housing, and pulled again. The pry bar slipped. Her knuckles rapped the stone wall. The pain was a distant fact — irrelevant.\n\nShe stepped back, breathing hard. The river’s growl filtered through the stone. She listened to the water, measured its pitch against the sound she had heard on the landing. Higher. Faster.\n\nThe spoke was wedged where the crack had spread. The pry bar could not reach the fulcrum needed. The gear train would not turn.\n\nMira set the bar down on the bench. She wiped her palms on her trousers. There was not time for another attempt. The warning bell had to ring before the lower ward filled. That required a working mechanism. That required a reeve’s authority to override the jam with a different solution — a winch, a ratchet, men with crowbars. She did not have the tools. She did not have the men.\n\nShe had her knowledge, and the knowledge was complete: the gear was beyond her ability to free alone.\n\nShe took her coat from the peg and shrugged it on. Her hand moved to the lantern, then stopped. The reeve’s office was three streets west. The cobbles would be slick, but the moon was high enough.\n\nShe pulled the door open and the damp night air hit her face. The river sound swelled, insistent.\n\n“It has to be done,” she said to the dark. Then she walked."
